<div class="portionheader">
	<h1>What is UV and its Impacts?</h1>
	<p>
		Ultraviolet (UV) rays are responsible for more than 95% of skin cancers, yet many mistakenly
		associate them solely with sunlight and heat. It's important to note that UV rays are
		invisible and cannot be felt, leading to potential confusion.
	</p>
	<div>
		<h2>Benefits</h2>
		<p>
			The sun aids in the production of vitamin D, a crucial nutrient for human health.
			Vitamin D facilitates the absorption of calcium and phosphorus from food, supporting
			bone development. The World Health Organization (WHO) suggests 5 to 15 minutes of sun
			exposure 2 to 3 times weekly to maintain adequate levels of vitamin D.
		</p>
		<h2>Risks</h2>
		<p>
			Protective measures such as sunscreen and sunglasses can mitigate UV radiation exposure.
			Sunburn indicates short-term overexposure, while prolonged exposure can result in
			premature aging and skin cancer. Failure to shield the eyes from UV radiation may
			increase the risk of sight-threatening eye diseases. Overexposure to UV radiation poses
			significant health risks, including cancer. Skin cancer is prevalent in Australia, with
			basal cell and squamous cell carcinomas being the most common types. Typically, these
			cancers develop on areas like the head, face, neck, hands, and arms, which receive the
			highest UV exposure. Melanoma, the deadliest form of skin cancer, is often attributed
			to UV radiation exposure. While anyone can experience adverse health effects from UV
			radiation, certain factors increase susceptibility:
		</p>
		<ol>
			<li>Prolonged sun exposure or history of sunburn</li>
			<li>Light-colored skin, hair, and eyes</li>
			<li>Use of certain medications or cosmetics that heighten skin and eye sensitivity to UV</li>
			<li>Family history of skin cancer</li>
			<li>Age over 50</li>
		</ol>
		<p>(https://www.cdc.gov/nceh/features/uv-radiation-safety/index.html)</p>
	</div>
</div>

